Henry Selick has a broader scope of profession compared to Géza von Cziffra. While both were directors and worked in animation, Selick is known for his work in stop motion animation across multiple films, including "The Nightmare Before Christmas," "James and the Giant Peach," and "Coraline," as well as his role as a producer and writer. Additionally, Selick studied at the Program in Experimental Animation at California Institute of the Arts, indicating a more diverse and specialized background in animation. In contrast, Géza von Cziffra was primarily a film director and screenwriter, known for his work in German and Austrian cinema, including the film "Kriminaltango" and its earlier version "Dangerous Guests."
